The medium sized green papaya salad is overpriced at $11. It's just a mound of shredded papaya (although well presented) with salad dressing poured over it and some peanuts and shrimp. We will be trying other Asian restaurants to see if we can find a better dish. The place is spacious and fairly clean although cardboard boxes are stored to the side. There are two beds behind a semi-wall which seem to be for the use of a couple of children. The bathroom is slightly more presentable than most similar eateries but still lacking in general cleanliness. Several customers seemed to be enjoying the all-you-can-eat buffet.

I'm really glad they have vegan options, but to say that this place serves Vietnamese dishes is very misleading. They only serve phở and a random dish with bún, there's zero Vietnamese on the menu so it's hard to translate from English to Vietnamese to try to understand what they serve. They don't serve bún chả. I had the Pad Thai and it was closer to spaghetti that a 3rd generation Italian immigrant would make if they were put on the spot. I was really looking forward to a menu that would have items similar to a restaurant next to a Vietnamese Buddhist temple but the reality is disappointing. At least soda refills are only $1. I hear that the owner is Vietnamese, so it's really disappointing that they aren't capitalizing on this and instead are making okay dishes from various countries.

Green Papaya is now on the corner of Young St. and Keeaumoku St. it’s now combined with Pot Pot Shabu Buffet under the same owner. So now you can get either the same old Green Papaya menu, which is excellent, or shabu shabu hot pot. The new space offers a lot more parking options than their old place and the restaurant space itself is larger and nicer. For the shabu shabu side, they have a ton of choices for meats and veggies in the refrigerators (see photos). And as for the Green Papaya, they still have the best spring rolls and Tom Yum on the island!
